pull_request.title: Create .NET 8 Fluent Garmin Library with FIT SDK Integration and Enhanced Repeat Structure Support
pull_request.body:
This PR implements a complete .NET 8 library that provides a fluent wrapper around Garmin's FIT SDK for creating workout files with proper repeat structure support. The library enables developers to easily generate Garmin-compatible workout files using an intuitive, builder-pattern API that follows Garmin's recommended patterns for intervals.

## Key Features

**Fluent API Design**: The library provides an easy-to-use builder pattern for creating workouts with comprehensive examples:

```csharp
// Basic workout pattern
var workout = new WorkoutBuilder()
    .Name("Morning Run")
    .Sport(Sport.Running)
    .WarmUp(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .AddTimeStep("Main Set", 20, 4, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .CoolDown(5, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .Build();

// Interval workout with repeat structure using option objects
var intervalOptions = new IntervalOptions 
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Distance,
    Value = 400,
    Zone = 4,
    TargetType = TargetType.Speed
};

var recoveryOptions = new RecoveryOptions
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Time,
    Value = 120,
    TargetType = TargetType.Open
};

var intervals = new WorkoutBuilder()
    .Name("Track Intervals")
    .Sport(Sport.Running)
    .WarmUp(10, 1)
    .AddIntervals("5x400m", 5, intervalOptions, recoveryOptions)
    .CoolDown(10, 1)
    .Build();
```

**Enhanced Method Naming**: Clear distinction between different types of workout steps:
- `AddTimeStep()` and `AddDistanceStep()` for individual workout segments (easy runs, tempo efforts, etc.)
- `AddIntervals()` for structured interval training with repeat patterns
- `AddRepeat()` for custom repeat structures with child steps

**Explicit Parameter Structure**: The `AddIntervals()` method requires explicit option objects for improved code clarity:
- Uses `IntervalOptions` and `RecoveryOptions` parameter objects that must be created and passed in
- Removes convenience overloads that built options internally for better API explicitness

**Proper Repeat Structure Support**: Uses Garmin's FIT SDK repeat patterns instead of manually creating individual steps:
- `AddIntervals()` method for easy interval creation with automatic repeat structure
- `AddRepeat()` method for custom repeat patterns with child steps
- Proper FIT file generation with parent repeat steps, child steps, and completion steps

**Comprehensive Target Support**: Full support for all Garmin target types including zones and custom ranges:
- Heart Rate zones (1-5) and custom BPM ranges (150-170)
- Speed zones (1-5) and custom speed ranges  
- Power zones (1-5) and custom wattage ranges
- Cadence custom ranges

**Enhanced Builder Methods**: Flexible warm-up and cool-down methods that accept target types:
```csharp
.WarmUp(15, 1, TargetType.Power)   // Power-based warm-up for cycling
.CoolDown(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)  // HR-based cool-down
```

**Pre-built Example Workouts**: Ready-to-use workout templates using repeat structures:
- `CreateIntervalWorkoutModel()` - 5x400m track intervals with proper repeat structure
- `CreateCyclingWorkoutModel()` - Power-based cycling intervals with 3x Build/Recovery pattern
- `CreateTempoRunModel()` - 20-minute tempo run

## Implementation Details

The library uses proper Garmin FIT SDK repeat patterns:
- **Repeat Steps**: Parent steps with `RepeatUntilStepsCmplt` duration type
- **Child Steps**: Interval and recovery steps contained within repeat structure  
- **Completion Steps**: Define how many times to repeat the pattern

This approach is more efficient and follows Garmin's recommended practices compared to manually creating individual interval steps.

## Project Structure

The solution file has been moved to the `src/` folder for better organization, with all projects properly referenced.

## Documentation

The README includes comprehensive examples covering:
- Basic workout patterns (warm up, main set, cool down) using `AddTimeStep`
- Interval workouts using repeat structures with explicit option objects
- Fartlek workouts with mixed interval patterns
- Custom repeat patterns and advanced usage
- Complete API documentation with real-world examples

## Testing

The library includes comprehensive test coverage with 23 unit tests covering:
- Model functionality and validation
- Fluent builder pattern behavior including new repeat methods
- File generation capabilities with repeat structure support
- All example workout scenarios using repeat patterns
- Custom target range functionality
- Edge cases and error handling

All tests pass and the library builds without warnings on .NET 8.

Fixes #1.

commits.message:
This commit introduces Lippy 2.0, a major upgrade that adds powerful new features for system interaction, help, and debugging.

Key enhancements include:

- **Improved Runner:** The `lippy` command now supports direct script execution (e.g., `lippy my_script.lpy`) and a `--help` flag for usage instructions.

- **System Commands:**
  - `(shell "...")`: Executes shell commands.
  - `(read-file "...")`: Reads content from files.
  - `(write-file "...")`: Writes content to files.

- **Core Bug Fix:** Fixed a fundamental bug by introducing a `Symbol` type to correctly distinguish between variable lookups and string literals.

- **Help System:**
  - `(doc <symbol>)`: Displays detailed documentation for a specific function.
  - `(help)`: Lists all available built-in functions.

- **Debugging Tools:**
  - `(trace <expression>)`: Prints a step-by-step, indented trace of an expression's evaluation.
  - `(env)`: Displays all variables in the current environment scope.

commits.message:
feat: Add spatial map for performance and fix FOV bug

This commit introduces two main changes:

1.  A spatial map has been added to optimize entity lookups by position. This significantly improves the performance of the map rendering. The `movement_system`, `death_system`, and `pickup_system` have been updated to maintain the spatial map.

2.  A bug in the fog of war system has been fixed. The `visibility_system` now correctly handles the day/night cycle, using a smaller FOV radius at night. A test has been added to verify this functionality.

This commit also refactors the `death_system` to be clearer and more robust. When an entity dies, it now creates a new, separate entity for the dropped item.

issue.title: Implement `RenewSession` call
issue.body:
#176 

## What I have made

Since the `AuthenticationInterceptor` handles the whole authentication including the session renewal, there is nothing needed in order to use the renew session functionality.

This can be tested very easily by simply reducing the access token TTL in the JWT Service to 1 minute or less.
Then you can test this behaviour by login in in the frontend, wait for a minute and then click on the reading list e.g.
Even the hover over the button should trigger the renew session event and the user should notice nothing in the frontend.

## Checklist

Either tick or cross out the items that do not apply (using \~\~example text\~\~) and give a reason why the item does
not apply.

- [ ] ~~I have updated the documentation accordingly and commented my code~~ Already implemented
- [ ] ~~I have added tests that prove my fix is effective or that my feature works~~ Already tested
- [ ] (for reviewer) I have checked the implementation against the requirements

issue.title: Issue: #330 Implement Transaction Management for Atomic Operations
issue.body:
CLOSES: #330

## Summary
- Implemented DatabaseTransaction utility class for atomic operations
- Automatic transaction support detection with graceful fallback to standalone MongoDB
- Updated all critical multi-write UserService operations to use transactions
- Enhanced User model with session-aware instance methods
- Comprehensive test coverage including unit and integration tests

## Changes Made
### Core Implementation
- **DatabaseTransaction.ts**: New utility class providing MongoDB transaction support
  - `withTransaction()`: High-level transaction wrapper
  - `withSession()`: Manual session management
  - `isTransactionSupported()`: Auto-detection of replica set support
  - `withFallback()`: Graceful degradation for standalone instances

### Database Layer Updates
- **UserServiceDatabase.ts**: All multi-write operations now use transactions
  - `markEmailVerified()`: Atomic email verification + token clearing
  - `updatePasswordAndClearTokens()`: Atomic password reset operations
  - `generateAndSaveResetToken()`: Atomic token generation
  - `generateAndSaveEmailToken()`: Atomic email token generation

### User Model Enhancements
- **User.ts**: Updated instance methods to accept session parameters
  - `generatePasswordResetToken()`: Now supports transactions
  - `generateEmailVerificationToken()`: Now supports transactions
  - `updateLastLogin()`: Now supports transactions

### Service Layer Integration
- **UserServiceAuth.ts**: Enhanced user creation process with atomic operations
  - User creation + email token generation now atomic
  - Improved error handling for transaction failures

### Testing
- **DatabaseTransaction.test.ts**: Comprehensive unit tests with mocking
- **UserServiceTransaction.integration.test.ts**: Real database integration tests
- All existing functionality maintained with backward compatibility

## Benefits
 **Data Consistency**: Multiple database writes are now atomic
 **Reliability**: No more partial state from failed operations
 **Backward Compatibility**: Works with both replica sets and standalone MongoDB
 **Error Handling**: Graceful fallback when transactions aren't supported
 **Performance**: Minimal overhead with automatic detection
 **Test Coverage**: Comprehensive testing of all transaction scenarios

## Test Results
-  All unit tests pass
-  Build completes successfully
-  Linting passes with no errors
-  Transaction fallback mechanisms work correctly

pull_request.title: Enhanced List and Timeline Views with Multiple View Options
pull_request.body:
## Summary
Added comprehensive List and Timeline views with multiple professional view options:

### List View Features
- **Dashboard View**: Professional overview with SVG pie charts and bar charts showing priority distribution and status analytics
- **Table View**: Clean data table with assignee avatars, priority bars, and status indicators  
- **Card View**: Modern card layout with visual priority indicators and progress tracking
- **Kanban View**: Drag-and-drop board organized by task status with swimlanes

### Timeline View Features
- **Gantt Chart**: Interactive timeline with enhanced task bars, milestone animations, and dependency visualization
- **Calendar View**: Monthly calendar with task scheduling, drag-and-drop, and backlog management
- **Activity Feed**: Real-time activity timeline with professional filters and clickable activity cards

### Technical Enhancements
- Enhanced project data with realistic timelines spanning August 2025 to March 2026
- Professional UI/UX with Tailwind CSS styling and smooth animations
- Interactive filtering systems and comprehensive statistics
- SVG-based charts and visual indicators
- Responsive design with mobile-first approach
- TypeScript integration with proper type definitions

### Files Modified
- `src/components/ListView.tsx` (new) - Multi-view list component
- `src/components/TimelineView.tsx` (new) - Multi-view timeline component  
- `src/types/projectData.ts` - Enhanced with comprehensive mock data
- `src/pages/Workspace.tsx` - Updated to integrate new components
- `src/index.css` - Added enhanced styling

## Test Plan
- [ ] Verify all view modes render correctly in both List and Timeline components
- [ ] Test interactive features (filtering, sorting, drag-and-drop)
- [ ] Validate responsive design across different screen sizes
- [ ] Confirm SVG charts and animations work properly
- [ ] Test data flow and state management

issue.title: A single keybind to cycle through on/zoom/off states
issue.body:
Hi,

I would like to be able to add a keybind that cycle through three states, on (tablet visible), zoomed (big tablet) then off.
Easier than having to look at a dedicated point to zoom the view especially when the tablet is on my knee (have to look way too low to have it zoomed).

So a click will display the table, another will zoom it, and the third will close it.

Thanks

comment.body:
Sorry, this is too specific/niche to be reasonable to support as a built-in feature.

You can do this via the existing [remote controls](https://openkneeboard.com/features/remote-controls/) via scripting, in combination with tools like voice attack or joy2key.

pull_request.body:
# For authors

## Description
Please:
1. Provide a summary of the modifications made and any associated issue (if applicable).
2. Include relevant context and motivation for the changes.
3. If this relates to a change in any website's frontend, kindly attach a screenshot of the adjustment from your localhost.
4. List any dependencies necessary for implementing this change.

## Fixes # (issue) Mention the issue number.

## Type of change
Please delete options that are not relevant.
- [ ] Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would cause existing functionality to not work as expected)
- [ ] This change requires a documentation update

## How Has This Been Tested?
Please describe the tests you conducted to verify your changes. These may involve creating new test scripts or updating existing ones.
- [ ] Added new test(s) in the ```tests``` folder
- [ ] Added new function(s) to an existing test(s) (e.g.: ```tests/testX.py```)
- [ ] No new tests added (Please explain the rationale in this case)

## Checklist
- [ ] My code follows the style guidelines mentioned in the Code/DevOps guides
- [ ] I have commented my code, particularly in hard-to-understand areas
- [ ] I have made corresponding changes to the documentation (e.g. MkDocs)
- [ ] My changes generate no new warnings
- [ ] I have added or updated tests (in the ```tests``` folder) that prove my fix is effective or that my feature works
- [ ] New and existing tests pass locally with my changes
- [ ] Any dependent changes have been merged and published in downstream modules

# For reviewers

## Checklist pre-approval
- [ ] Is there enough documentation?
- [ ] If a new feature has been added, or a bug fixed, has a test been added to confirm good behavior?
- [ ] Does the test(s) successfully test edge/corner cases?
- [ ] Does the PR pass the tests? (if the repository has continuous integration)

## Checklist post-approval
- [ ] Does this PR merge ```develop``` into ```main```? If so, please make sure to add a prefix (feat/fix/chore) and/or a suffix BREAKING CHANGE (if it's a major release) to your commit message.
- [ ] Does this PR close an issue? If so, please make sure to descriptively close this issue when the PR is merged.

## Checklist post-merge
- [ ] When you approve of the PR, merge and close it (Read this [article](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/configuring-branches-and-merges-in-your-repository/configuring-pull-request-merges/about-merge-methods-on-github) to know about different merge methods on GitHub)
- [ ] Did this PR merge ```develop``` into ```main``` and is it suppose to run an automated release workflow (if applicable)? If so, please make sure to check under the "Actions" tab to see if the workflow has been initiated, and return later to verify that it has completed successfully.

issue.title: [perf]: take a long time to respond for the first time inserting pairs in large files

milestone.title: v0.7
milestone.description: I'm working on v0.7 in a private repo currently...

issue.body:
In a large file (a 200MB json file), when I enter insert mode and press any type of pairs, such as a '(', it will takes about 10 seconds to respond for the first time. After that, it will respond normally, when I press '(' again.

Is there any way to solve this?

comment.body: There's a `p`(priority) flag which which needs to be set to a higher number for it to work... (see the default config for reference)
